Myth: In the Era of the Hollow Reed, the Bamboo Stalk grew taller and harder than any other in the grove. He prided himself on his empty, perfect cylinder, believing that purity meant containing nothing. He watched the Mud below, thick and chaotic, filled with decaying leaves and crawling insects, and sneered at its messiness. "You are clogged with filth," the Bamboo whistled in the wind. "I am a vessel of clean air."

But the Mud bubbled back, "I am full of life's ingredients. You are clean, but you are barren." The Bamboo felt a hollow ache in his segments; he was tall, yes, but he was merely a pipe for the wind's lonely song.

He called to the Monsoon, the spirit of the heavy rains. "Fill me," the Bamboo begged, dreading the weight. The Monsoon obliged, pouring water into his open top until he bent near breaking. The water brought silt and tiny seeds from the canopy. The pressure was immense, cracking his rigid walls. Yet, as he fractured, the seeds caught in his splinters found wet soil within him. He was no longer a perfect, empty flute, but a nursery. He learned that one must sometimes be cluttered and cracked to nurture new growth.

