He climbed to the very spine of the world, where the rock was hardest. He struck his great curved horns against the granite, shattering them into dust. He did not mourn his loss. He mixed the dust of his strength with his own saliva to create a mortar, a living glue. He descended the slopes, packing the mortar between the loose stones.

He worked until his hooves were worn and his head was bare, binding the mountain together. The slide stopped. The slopes held firm, allowing soil to gather and ancient pines to take root in the stabilized rock. Now, the mountains stand tall and unmoving, held together by the Ram’s sacrifice, proving that true strength is not just in standing high, but in holding the ground for others to grow.
